<body>
<center>
<!WA0><IMG SRC="http://infopad.eecs.berkeley.edu/images/title.gif" alt="Welcome to the Infopad WWW Server">
</center>
The goal of the InfoPad research project is to
develop the hardware, software and mobile network support which will allow
ubiquitous, wireless access of realtime
multimedia data from high speed networks
using an inexpensive, portable terminal. It in effect is a "network terminal",
but with the additional capability of portability.
The most recent descriptions of the project can be found in the
<!WA1><A href="http://infopad.eecs.berkeley.edu/infopad-ftp/reports/A.Multimedia.Communication.System.Providing.Wireless.Access"> student summaries </A>
, in these <!WA2><A href="http://infopad.eecs.berkeley.edu/infopad-ftp/slides/ARPA.Presentations/ARPA.7.95/infopad_overview"> slides </A> and this recent 
<!WA3><A href="http://infopad.eecs.berkeley.edu/~rb/Overview"> overview </A>.

<p>

This work is primarily funded by <!WA4><A href="http://www.arpa.mil"> ARPA </A>
with additional support from our
industrial partners which include
<!WA5><A href="http://www.intel.com/"> Intel </A>,
<!WA6><A href="http://www.ibm.com/"> IBM </A>, 
<!WA7><A href="http://www.ericsson.com/"> Ericsson </A>,
<!WA8><A href="http://www.motorola.com/"> Motorola </A>,
<!WA9><A href="http://www.nsc.com/"> National Semiconductor </A> and <!WA10><A href="http://www.ti.com/corp/docs/home.htm"> Texas Instruments </A>.
<p>
We are all part of the
<!WA11><a href="http://www.eecs.berkeley.edu">
Electrical Engineering and Computer Science Department</a>
at the
<!WA12><a href="http://www.berkeley.edu">
University of California, Berkeley. </a>
